('english', 'NECO', 'I have eventually found the book. "Eventually" means:', 'actually', 'lately', 'presently', 'finally', NULL, 'D', '"Eventually" means in the end, after a long time — nearest in meaning to "finally."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'It is not good for a child to be unduly inquisitive. "Inquisitive" means:', 'naughty', 'playful', 'curious', 'troublesome', NULL, 'C', '"Inquisitive" means having a strong desire to know or learn things — nearest in meaning to "curious."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Kofi is rather audacious; he jumps off high fences. "Audacious" means:', 'daring', 'smart', 'active', 'agile', NULL, 'A', '"Audacious" means showing a willingness to take surprisingly bold risks — nearest in meaning to "daring."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The criminal approached the crowd menacingly. "Menacingly" means:', 'stealthily', 'cunningly', 'calculatedly', 'threateningly', NULL, 'D', '"Menacingly" means in a way that suggests danger or harm — nearest in meaning to "threateningly."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'He said that they _________ painting the house by then.', 'will have finished', 'will finish', 'would have finished', 'would finish', NULL, 'C', 'The sentence requires the future perfect tense in reported speech — "would have finished" is correct as it indicates an action completed before a point in the past.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'I will wear my _________ Dress to the dance.', 'blue silk new', 'new blue silk', 'silk new blue', 'silk blue new', NULL, 'B', 'The correct adjective order in English is: opinion, size, age, shape, color, origin, material, purpose. So "new blue silk" follows the correct sequence.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'If I _________ an eagle, I would fly to distant lands.', 'was', 'were', 'am', 'be', NULL, 'B', '"Were" is used in conditional/subjunctive sentences expressing hypothetical or imaginary situations, e.g. "If I were an eagle..."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The teacher needs _________ to write the note on the chalkboard.', 'chalks', 'some chalk', 'chalk', 'many chalks', NULL, 'C', '"Chalk" is an uncountable noun and should not be pluralized. The correct form is simply "chalk."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The man said that he _________ eaten there previously.', 'had', 'ate', 'has eaten there before', 'had eaten there yesterday', NULL, 'A', 'In reported speech, the past perfect tense "had eaten" is used to show that the action occurred before the reporting time.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'To be healthy we need to eat a _________ diet everyday.', 'balanced', 'complete', 'mixed', 'delicious', NULL, 'A', '"Balanced diet" is the standard collocation in health and nutrition — a diet that contains all the necessary nutrients in the right proportions.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'I can rustle _________ an omelette at least.', 'out', 'up', 'in', 'off', NULL, 'B', '"Rustle up" is the correct phrasal verb meaning to prepare or make something quickly, especially food.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Banku was _________ unhappy after the fight.', 'very', 'too', 'much', 'such', NULL, 'A', '"Very" is the correct adverb to intensify the adjective "unhappy" in this context.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Everything would be _________ cheaper in the sales.', 'greatly', 'considerably', 'strongly', 'most', NULL, 'B', '"Considerably" is the appropriate adverb meaning by a large or significant amount — fits "cheaper" well.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The boot of my new car was _________ in the accident.', 'cracked', 'broken', 'dented', 'chipped', NULL, 'C', '"Dented" is the most appropriate word for the boot of a car being damaged — it means having a depression or hollow made by a blow.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Parents should create an environment _________ their children can grow.', 'which', 'what', 'from where', 'in which', NULL, 'D', '"In which" is the correct relative pronoun phrase to introduce the relative clause describing the environment.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'In spite of his shortcomings, we admire him _________.', 'yet', 'though', 'but', 'however', NULL, 'C', '"But" is the appropriate conjunction to show contrast in this sentence.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Amadi''s plan _________ at the last moment.', 'fell down', 'fell off', 'fell on', 'fell through', NULL, 'D', '"Fell through" is the correct phrasal verb meaning a plan or deal failed or didn''t succeed.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'You think I am hungry, _________?', 'am I', 'aren''t I', 'don''t you', 'I', NULL, 'C', 'The question tag should reflect the main clause subject and tense. "You think" uses "you" and "think," so the tag is "don''t you?"', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Maria _________ tears when she was told that she had failed the final examination.', 'broke to', 'broke up', 'broke with', 'broke into', NULL, 'D', '"Broke into tears" is the correct phrasal verb expression meaning to suddenly start crying.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Jide _________ before I arrived.', 'could', 'must have eaten', 'can have eaten', 'had eaten', NULL, 'D', '"Had eaten" is the correct past perfect form to indicate an action that happened before another past action (before I arrived).', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'He claimed to be an expert, but he knew next to _________ about it.', 'everything', 'nothing', 'something', 'anything', NULL, 'B', '"Knew next to nothing" is the correct idiomatic expression meaning he knew almost nothing about it.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', '_________ the textbooks, he advised his daughter to face her studies.', 'Having being bought', 'Having bought', 'Having been bought', 'Having buy', NULL, 'B', '"Having bought" is the correct perfect participle form — it indicates the action was completed before the main clause action.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Deficiency of _________ just one essential vitamin may cause illness.', 'on', 'in', 'from', 'of', NULL, 'B', '"Deficiency in" is the correct collocation — one is deficient in a nutrient or vitamin.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'This is the _________ he has submitted his assignment since joining the class.', 'earliest', 'early', 'latest', 'soonest', NULL, 'A', '"Earliest" is the correct superlative form to indicate the first time something has happened.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'It is wise to _________ with what one has rather than go on borrowing.', 'make up', 'make out', 'make do', 'make over', NULL, 'C', '"Make do" is the correct phrasal verb meaning to manage with what is available, even if it is not ideal.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The teacher was _________ hasty in meting out punishment.', 'more', 'much', 'scarcely', 'somewhat', NULL, 'D', '"Somewhat" is the appropriate adverb meaning to a moderate degree — fits "hasty" in this context.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Everybody should treat their parents with respect, _________?', 'should they', 'shouldn''t they', 'shouldn''t we', 'should we', NULL, 'B', '"Shouldn''t they" is the correct negative question tag for the positive statement "Everybody should treat their parents with respect."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The experienced clerk found herself at _________ crossroad.', 'a crossroads', 'some crossroads', 'any crossroads', 'the crossroads', NULL, 'A', '"At a crossroads" is the correct expression meaning at a point where a decision must be made.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'We are playing _________ the problems of the company.', 'off', 'up', 'out', 'down', NULL, 'D', '"Playing down" is the correct phrasal verb meaning to minimize the importance of something.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'You _________ have walked home alone so late at night.', 'would not', 'might not', 'ought not to', 'need not to', NULL, 'C', '"Ought not to" is the correct modal expression indicating something that was inadvisable or wrong to do.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Did you notice that the _________ had been removed?', 'price''s tag', 'prices tag', 'price tag', 'prices'' tag', NULL, 'C', '"Price tag" is the standard compound noun — no apostrophe is needed as it is a compound noun not a possessive.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'It is mandatory that consumables should have _________ dates.', 'sell-by', 'sell-out', 'sell-off', 'sell-on', NULL, 'A', '"Sell-by date" is the term used for the date by which a product should be sold — the standard expression in commerce.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Don''t judge the boy _________ his past.', 'by', 'from', 'at', 'for', NULL, 'A', '"Judge by" is the correct collocation — "by" is the correct preposition used to indicate the criteria for judgment.', NULL);
